abstract: If Dave Winfield is to become a Yankee, he apparently will have to do it as a free agent. Winfield said last night that he would not withdraw his name from the free-agent draft, practically ending any chance the Yankees had to acquire him in a trade with the San Diego Padres.
headline_main: Winfield To Stay In Draft; Winfield Will Remain a Free Agent Wants Yanks to Have a Chance

abstract: PHILADELPHIA EVEN before Tug McGraw  soared into space in celebration of the Philadelphia Phillies' first World Series success, George Steinbrenner was plotting to overthrow the new champions with the peppermint pin-striped uniforms.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 22--The baseball season ended ceremonially today with cascades of confetti in Philadelphia and Kansas City, as the Phillies and Royals took World Series curtain calls and braced for a winter of perhaps significant changes.

abstract: LOUISVILLE, Ky., Oct. 21--Notes on a campaign day with Ronald Reagan. Route: Virginia to Taft country in Ohio, then to Kentucky. Time: Monday last. Destination: White House.

PHILADELPHIA GEORGE DALLAS GREEN is a  big, unflappable guy who has been scheming and struggling to escape from a job that most other baseball men scheme and struggle to get throughout their adult lives. He is manager of the Philadelphia Phillies, who are champions of North America now and will be champions when the sun rises again on William Penn's greene countrie towne.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 21--For the first time in their 98-year history, the Philadelphia Phillies won the World Series tonight when Steve Carlton and Tug McGraw pitched them to a 4-1 victory over the Kansas City Royals.

abstract: PHILADELPHIA, Oct. 21--With an icebag strapped to his left arm and with a champagne bottle in his right hand, Tug McGraw was enjoying the first World Series championship in the 98-year history of the Philadelphia Phillies tonight when he was asked what he was going to drink to celebrate.
